Nothing new; workaround is still: https://github.com/algolia/instantsearch.js/issues/985#issuecomment-388899593

```js
instantsearch({
  routing: {
    stateMapping: {
      stateToRoute(uiState) {
        return {
          turbolinks: true,
          ... uiState,
        };
      },
      routeToState({turbolinks, ...routeState}) {
        return routeState
      }
    }
  }
});
```

> Nothing new; workaround is still: [#985 (comment)](https://github.com/algolia/instantsearch.js/issues/985#issuecomment-388899593)
> 
> ```js
> instantsearch({
>   routing: {
>     stateMapping: {
>       stateToRoute(uiState) {
>         return {
>           turbolinks: true,
>           ... uiState,
>         };
>       },
>       routeToState({turbolinks, ...routeState}) {
>         return routeState
>       }
>     }
>   }
> });
> ```

Is this still the recommended workaround with the latest instantsearch and turbo(links) versions? Unfortunately it doesn't seem to have any effect for me (apart from adding `turbolinks=true` to the generated URL).

~~Here is the working solution in 2024, with current versions of InstantSearch.js 4 & Turbo 8 ([Source](https://discuss.hotwired.dev/t/back-button-not-working/3012/2)):~~

```js
instantsearch({
  routing: {
    router: history({
      cleanUrlOnDispose: false,
      push: (url) => {
        window.history.pushState({}, null, url);
        Turbo.navigator.history.push(url);
      },
    }),
  },
})
```

👇  [See below for actual solution](https://github.com/algolia/instantsearch/issues/2998#issuecomment-2739987150)

@Spone Thanks that worked mostly for me but i had to use `replace` instead of `push` `Turbo.navigator.history.replace(url);`

With using `push`, i could go back with the back button when leaving the search page but after that, every back button click would not do anything until i reach the last item in the history on the search page (initial state when loading the search page). 

With `replace` i can traverse back properly and routing works as intended.

> With using push, i could go back with the back button when leaving the search page but after that, every back button click would not do anything until i reach the last item in the history on the search page (initial state when loading the search page).

This stems from `window.history.pushState({}, null, url);` and `Turbo.navigator.history.push(url);` meaning essentially the same thing.

See: https://github.com/hotwired/turbo/blob/3138f17574c27127c78697986ab1ac95dcca4d70/src/core/drive/history.js#L33
and: https://github.com/hotwired/turbo/blob/3138f17574c27127c78697986ab1ac95dcca4d70/src/core/drive/history.js#L45

So it should be:
```js
instantsearch({
  routing: {
    router: history({
      cleanUrlOnDispose: false,
      push: (url) => {
         Turbo.navigator.history.push(new URL(url))
      },
    }),
  },
})
```

The reason why we needed to call both before was because Turbo's push expects a URL object, instead of a string.
